{{page-title "Documentation — Career Data"}}
<div class="container mx-auto max-w-3xl py-6 px-4 space-y-6">

  <Panel::Card>
    <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-2">Career Data</h1>
    <p
      class="text-blue-700 bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded px-4 py-3 text-sm font-medium mb-4"
    >
      Career Data is the most important resource in Career Caddy. Set it up
      before using any AI feature.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-600">
      Career Data is a single markdown document that describes you as a
      professional. It is the context the AI reads before doing anything —
      scoring your resume, writing a cover letter, drafting an answer, or
      generating a summary. The quality of every AI output is directly tied to
      the quality of your Career Data.
    </p>
    {{! <img src="" alt="screenshot of the Career Data editor with content filled in" /> }}
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">Why It Matters</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-3">
      Most AI tools for job seeking give you generic output because they only
      know what you tell them in the moment. Career Caddy is different: every
      request includes your Career Data as a standing brief. The AI knows your
      background, your style, and what you're looking for — without you having
      to re-explain it each time.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-600">
      Over time, the feedback loop improves this further. Cover letters and
      answers you mark as
      <strong>favorites</strong>
      are woven back into the AI's understanding of your voice. It gradually
      learns to write more like you and less like a template.
    </p>
    {{! <img src="" alt="screenshot showing the favorite button on a cover letter" /> }}
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">What to Include</h2>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-600 list-disc list-inside">
      <li><strong>Work history with outcomes</strong>
        — not just responsibilities, but results. "Reduced API latency by 40%"
        beats "worked on performance."</li>
      <li><strong>Technical skills</strong>
        — languages, frameworks, tools, platforms. Be specific.</li>
      <li><strong>Soft skills and working style</strong>
        — how you collaborate, lead, communicate.</li>
      <li><strong>Education and certifications</strong>
        — degrees, courses, credentials.</li>
      <li><strong>Writing voice</strong>
        — notes on how you write: "direct and concise, no buzzwords," "warm but
        professional," etc.</li>
      <li><strong>Target roles and industries</strong>
        — what you're looking for and why.</li>
      <li><strong>Sample writing</strong>
        — paste in a paragraph or two you've written that you're proud of. This
        is gold for the AI.</li>
    </ul>
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">How to Write It</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-3">
      Write in first person, present tense where appropriate. Don't just list
      duties — explain the impact. Don't aim for brevity; the AI can handle
      length. What it struggles with is vagueness. Be specific.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-600">
      There is no required format. Markdown headings help organize sections, but
      the AI reads the whole document — structure is for your benefit.
    </p>
    {{! <img src="" alt="screenshot of Career Data in edit mode with markdown formatting" /> }}
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">Example Career Data</h2>
